<div id="review_309568695" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/309568695" />
    <a title="Dan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/870755-dan"><img alt="Dan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643916040p2/870755.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/309568695?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dan" href="/user/show/870755-dan">Dan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Dan by: </span>
      The Great and Powerful Emily
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/870755-dan?shelf=homework-from-the-ladies">homework-from-the-ladies</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/870755-dan?shelf=2012">2012</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer309568695" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6674243538249611918">Thriller writer Douglas Preston moved to Italy, only to find out the nearby olive grove was the scene of a ghasty double murder. Preston and the journalist originally covering the investigation, Mario Spezi, dig into the case of the Monster of Florence, even winding up being investigated themselves...<br/><br/>I know I made the synopsis sound like a thriller but this is non-fiction, the account of an Italian serial killer and his murders. It&apos;s a fascinating journey into a reign of terror that lasted decad</span>
  <span id="freeText6674243538249611918" style="display:none">Thriller writer Douglas Preston moved to Italy, only to find out the nearby olive grove was the scene of a ghasty double murder. Preston and the journalist originally covering the investigation, Mario Spezi, dig into the case of the Monster of Florence, even winding up being investigated themselves...<br /><br />I know I made the synopsis sound like a thriller but this is non-fiction, the account of an Italian serial killer and his murders. It's a fascinating journey into a reign of terror that lasted decades and into the psychology of the killer, the Italian press and justice system.<br /><br />Preston writes the tale in an engaging way, making me forget I was reading nonfiction at times. The Monster of Florence's crimes were brutal and the descriptions of the murders can be somewhat graphic. Each of the suspects almost seemed tailor-made for a book of this type. Spezi's, and later Preston's, frustration was almost tangible. The one thing that reminded me that I wasn't reading fiction is that the Monster of Florence was never caught!<br /><br />Fun fact: The Monster of Florence, the man, not the book, was a partial inspiration for parts of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/32418.Hannibal__Hannibal_Lecter___3_" title="Hannibal (Hannibal Lecter, #3) by Thomas Harris" rel="nofollow noopener">Hannibal</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/12455.Thomas_Harris" title="Thomas Harris" rel="nofollow noopener">Thomas Harris</a>.<br /><br />That's about all I can say without revealing too much. Read it yourself and get drawn into the web of deceit, murder, mutilation, vengeance, and corruption. And you'd be well served to never get suspected of a crime in Italy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6674243538249611918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


