<span id="freeTextContainer3655458236754527969">I am amazed how awful the justice system is in Italy. It&apos;s not that the Monster of Florence case is unsolved. That happens a lot. It&apos;s the clear dysfunction of how the case was handled. The innocent people who were falsely accused. The criminal acts done by the very people who were supposed to honoring the law itself. I was gripped from start to finish pausing only to calm the blood that was boiling in me from the shear stupidity of it all. The case was fascinating and horrific. Innocent lives t</span>
  <span id="freeText3655458236754527969" style="display:none">I am amazed how awful the justice system is in Italy. It's not that the Monster of Florence case is unsolved. That happens a lot. It's the clear dysfunction of how the case was handled. The innocent people who were falsely accused. The criminal acts done by the very people who were supposed to honoring the law itself. I was gripped from start to finish pausing only to calm the blood that was boiling in me from the shear stupidity of it all. The case was fascinating and horrific. Innocent lives taken so viciously was unsettling. Again I find that the humanity for the victims was a bit lost in the book. I get why, but I find I like the book more when the victims are given a sense of dignity. They had lives prior to their awful ends. All in all if you enjoy true Crime, I would recommend this book.</span>
